1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 $5 {There are many ways to play against the
Pirc, but this is one of the most energetic and aggressive. Black should
always be careful as White is threatening to take the initiative very quickly.
From a positional standpoint, central pawns ensure a space advantage as well.}
Bg7 5. Nf3 c5 $5 {The second most popular move. Black tries to contest White's
center before bringing his king to safety, creating a strong tension.} 6. Bb5+
$1 {Taking immediate advantage of the fact that Black hasn't castled yet.} (6.
e5 {is interesting, but after} Nfd7 $1 (6... dxe5 $2 7. dxe5 $1 {Whenever
Black king is still on e8, White should take advantage of that fact and
recapture with the d-pawn, as after the trade of queens Nd5-c7 idea becomes
very annoying.} Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 $1 {Again the best move, keeping the Nc3 ready
to jump to d5. Now Black has some problems with his development.} Ng4 (8...
Nfd7 9. Nd5 Kd8 10. Ng5 $18) 9. Ke1 Nc6 10. Nd5 O-O (10... Kd8 11. h3 Nh6 12.
Be3 e6 13. Nc3 b6 14. Rd1+ Ke7 15. Bf2 $1 $36 {And black king is still in
danger.}) 11. Bb5 $1 {White is threatening to win material, and after} e6 12.
Bxc6 bxc6 13. Ne7+ Kh8 14. h3 Nh6 15. Nxc8 $1 Rfxc8 16. g4 $1 {in addition to
the bad pawn structure, Black is having problems with the misplaced knight.})
7. exd6 O-O $1 {a complicated position arises. The games in database show that
Black has good chances as he is now ahead in development.}) 6... Bd7 (6... Nfd7
{might look safe, but then White can play} 7. dxc5 $1 dxc5 8. e5 $1 {and
Black's position is already unpleasant} O-O (8... a6 9. Bc4 e6 $2 {closing the
diagonal, but leaving dark squares weakened.} 10. a4 $1 {securing a strong
square for the light-squared bishop, from where it can prevent black from
breaking with f7-f6. In addition, white is also preventing any expansion on
the queenside.} O-O 11. Be3 Nc6 12. h4 $36 {and White had a strong initiative
in Bajarani,U (2494)-Bayramov,E (2051) Baku 2017}) 9. O-O a6 10. Bd3 Nb6 11.
Be3 Qc7 12. Qe2 {Black has a difficult time to finish his development, as f6
is not advisable} Bg4 (12... f6 13. exf6 exf6 14. Qf2 N8d7 15. a4 $1 a5 16. f5
$1 {and White has a clear advantage.}) 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nc6 15. Qf2 $1 $16
{Artemiev,V (2560)-Iskandarov,M (2406) Baku 2013} (15. Bxc5 $2 Nxe5 $1)) (6...
Nc6 $2 {was played recently in a blitz tie-break Wey Yi (2707)-Rapport,R (2717)
Yancheng 2016, but it is very difficult to believe in such moves.} 7. d5 a6 8.
Ba4 b5 9. dxc6 Qc7 10. e5 $1 dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 12. Bf4 bxa4 13. Qd5 $16 {
Vocaturo,D (2574)-Movsziszian,K (2458) Barcelona 2016}) 7. e5 $1 {White keeps
creating threats to disturb Black's development.} Ng4 (7... Nh5 $2 {Shomoev,A 
(2578)-Mamedyarov,S (2756) Jurmala 2015} 8. dxc5 $1 $146 {is just better for
White}) 8. Bxd7+ ({there are many beautiful quick draws in the database with} 
8. e6 fxe6 9. Ng5 Bxb5 10. Nxe6 Bxd4 11. Nxd8 Bf2+ 12. Kd2 Be3+ $11 {This,
naturally, is not our objective :)}) 8... Qxd7 {Black should avoid the
thematic break on e6.} (8... Nxd7 $2 9. e6 $1 fxe6 10. Ng5 {and White has a
strong attack, my latest game in this position went} cxd4 $2 {only here I
didn't play the best continuation.} 11. Qxg4 $2 ({The right way is:} 11. Nxe6
Qa5 12. Nxg7+ Kf7 13. Qxg4 dxc3 14. b4 $1 $18) 11... dxc3 12. Nxe6 cxb2 13.
Nxg7+ Kf7 14. Qe6+ Kxg7 15. Bxb2+ Nf6 16. O-O-O $36 {although even here White
had a strong initiative; Quintiliano,R (2484) -Bruce,S (2152) Florianopolis
2017}) 9. h3 {Not the most common, but when analyzing this variation I found
this move very interesting.} (9. d5 {is the main move, but after} dxe5 10. h3
e4 $1 11. Nxe4 ({maybe} 11. hxg4 $5 exf3 12. Qxf3 {preparing 0-0-0 is an
interesting attempt to get some initiative.}) 11... Nf6 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {
I think that Black might be OK. He will finish his development soon and can
find good squares for his pieces.}) 9... cxd4 (9... Nh6 $6 10. dxc5 $1 {
This move is seen in some positions in this line and can be very annoying for
black. Positionally, it is easy to explain: White has a lead in development 
(just look at poorly placed black knights) and he is taking active measures in
the center. When you have such an advantage, you should create direct threats
or open the position as soon as possible, because the opponent is usually not
in the position to react appropriately.} dxe5 11. fxe5 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Nd7 {
Grischuk,A (2763)-Mamedyarov,S (2726) Astana 2012 and here with} (12... Nc6
$142) 13. Ne4 $1 {White would have kept a nice advantage.} Ng8 14. Bd2 $1 f5 (
14... Nxe5 15. Bc3 f6 16. Nxe5 fxe5 17. Re1 $16) 15. exf6 Ngxf6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6
17. c3 Nxc5 18. Kc2 O-O-O 19. Be3 $14 {with a superior pawn structure in the
endgame.}) 10. Qxd4 Nc6 {It makes a big difference which knight should be
moved first.} (10... Nh6 {In this critical position White should play} 11. Qf2
$1 {an excellent prophylactic move, anticipating Nf5 and putting the queen to
a nice square, from where it can take action on both sides of the board.
Black's position might not be especially dangerous for a while, but he should
be careful in the long run.} Nc6 12. Bd2 O-O (12... dxe5 13. O-O-O $1 $146 {
This is my idea, which of course needs some practical tests. White's position
looks very promising:} exf4 (13... O-O 14. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 15. fxe5 Qc6 16. Rhe1 {
looks more comfortable for White.}) 14. Bxf4 $44 {White has a clear
compensation for the pawn in the view of better development, for example} Qf5 (
14... Qc8 $142 15. Qd2 Nf5 16. g4 O-O $1 17. gxf5 Qxf5 $13) 15. Nd5 O-O-O $5 {
Black mimics white's queenside castling, but his king is not safe there.} (
15... O-O 16. g4 Qe4 17. b3 $1 {suddenly, the queen is in danger of being
trapped.} Nb4 $8 18. Rhe1 Nxa2+ 19. Kb1 Nc3+ $1 20. Nxc3 Qxf4 21. Nd5 Qb8 22.
Rxe7 $14 {and it is still White who is pressing.}) 16. Nh4 Qe4 17. Rhe1 Qa4 18.
Rxe7 $1 $18) (12... f5 $6 {aiming to transfer the knight to f7 and, at the
same time, stopping expansion ideas on the kingside.} 13. O-O-O O-O 14. Nd5 $1
Nf7 15. Bc3 $16 {and White had a comfortable advantage in Grandelius,N (2566)
-Tan Zongyi (2466) Reykjavik 2013}) 13. O-O-O Rac8 14. g4 $1 {Black's position
is quite passive and, on top of it, he needs to deal with ideas like f5 - gxf5
- g5, winning the knight.} Nb4 $6 {Desperate situations requires desperate
measures, but if Black is looking for exchange sacrifices already, we get a
good idea how much uncomfortable his position is.} (14... dxe5 15. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5
16. fxe5 f5 17. exf6 Rxf6 18. Qxa7 $16) 15. a3 Rxc3 16. bxc3 $1 Nd5 {Smirnov,P
(2600)-Zablotsky,S (2533) Vladivostok 2015 now the simple} 17. Qxa7 $18 {
is winning}) 11. Qe4 Nh6 {Compared to the previous notes, the queen is more
exposed on e4.} 12. Be3 (12. g4 O-O-O $1 {looks good for Black, for example}
13. Bd2 {Petrov,A (2394)-Rakhmangulov,A (2351) Taganrog 2014 is too slow} f5 $1
14. exf6 exf6 15. O-O-O f5 $1 {and Black is already looking for the initiative}
) 12... dxe5 (12... Nf5 {is very natural, trying to solve the knight's problem}
13. Bf2 dxe5 (13... h5 $2 {does not solve Black's opening problems.} 14. O-O-O
h4 15. Rhe1 $16) 14. fxe5 Qe6 ({black also has a tactical possibility:} 14...
Nxe5 $5 15. Nxe5 Qe6 {now the game takes on a forced sequence, which ends with
a slightly easier endgame for White:} 16. O-O-O $1 Bxe5 17. Rhe1 Bxc3 18. Qxb7
$1 Qc8 $8 19. Qxc8+ (19. Qb5+ $5 $146 {could be an improvement over the
existing theory:} Kf8 20. bxc3 Qxc3 21. Rd7 {White has an unpleasant
initiative, which compensates for the pawn. If, for example} a6 22. Qc5 $1 Qxc5
23. Bxc5 Rc8 $8 24. Bxe7+ Kg7 25. Ba3 $14 {White reaches a similar endgame,
with some winning chances due the passed c-pawn.}) 19... Rxc8 20. bxc3 Rc7 21.
g4 $1 Ng7 22. Bg3 Rb7 (22... Rc6 $142 $1 {looks like a safer option for Black,
and it is recommended by Marin, but I think that White keeps some slight
practical chances with} 23. Be5 {although detailed analysis shows that Black
is able to equalize in two different ways:} Rg8 $1 {should be the correct
answer by Black. It doesn't look like a natural move, though, which makes it
more difficult to find in over-the-board play.} (23... O-O {is the most
natural response, however it leaves the 7th rank undefended.} 24. Rd7 f6 (24...
Ra6 25. Bd4 Rxa2 26. Rexe7 a6 27. Kd2 {White pieces are very active, and again
the passed c-pawn can be dangerous in the endgame.}) 25. Bf4 Ne6 26. Bd2 Kf7
27. Rxa7 {+/=/= The computer indicates many moves with equality. This probably
means that Black can eventually mobilize his pieces and limit white's progress.
But I like White's chances in practice - if Black makes one or two
inaccuracies, the queenside's pawns could become very dangerous.}) (23... f6
24. Bd6 $1 e6 {now White changes the target} 25. Rf1 $1 {Unexpectedly, Black
has a spetacular resource:} g5 $3 {White still can slowly try to improve the
position with} 26. c4 $5 ({but the hasty} 26. Rxf6 $2 {is met by} Rxd6 $1 27.
Rxd6 Ke7)) 24. g5 $1 {Black's position is a little strange, but he can solve
the problems with} Ne6 (24... Nf5 25. Re4 $1 h6 26. h4 {still offers White
better chances.}) 25. h4 h6 $1 {a nice sacrifice that gets Black out of a
cramped position.} 26. gxh6 f6 27. Bd6 $1 Kf7 $1 28. Bb4 {Rd1-d7 is threatened,
therefore:} Rc7 29. Rd2 Rh8 30. Rde2 Rc6 31. Rd2 Rc7 $11) 23. Re4 $1 {Shirov,A
(2691)-Zaragatski,I (2472) Germany 2015} O-O 24. Rb4 $1 $14 {With the passed
queenside pawns and a very active bishop, this endgame is difficult for Black.}
) 15. O-O-O $1 {White should always be ready to sacrifice this pawn in order
to finish the development and obtain initiative:} Nxe5 16. Rhe1 Nc6 {Wey Yi 
(2718)-Liu Qingnan (2523) Xinghua 2015} 17. Qxe6 fxe6 18. Nb5 {A nice knight
maneouvre} O-O 19. Nc7 Rad8 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 (20... Nxd8 21. Bxa7) 21. Nxe6 $16 {
g4 is still an unpleasant threat in some positions and the Ne6 is dominating
Black's position, while Bf2 is putting pressure on the queenside. In other
words, this is a tough endgame for black.}) 13. fxe5 O-O (13... O-O-O 14. O-O
Qe6 15. Rad1 $1 {the e5-pawn is untouchable, for now} Nf5 16. Bf4 Rxd1 17. Rxd1
Rd8 {Black is trying to relieve the position through exchanges, but his
problems persist, as we shall see:} 18. Rxd8+ Nxd8 19. g4 $1 {the poor knight
needs to return to h6.} Qb6+ 20. Kg2 Nh6 21. Nd5 {and so does the queen...} Qe6
22. Qc4+ Nc6 23. b4 $18 {with an exemplary domination by White in Shirov,A 
(2719) -Markowski,T (2629) Warsaw 2009}) 14. O-O Qe6 {Gu,X (2324)-Tan,Z (2509)
Yangzhou 2016. Here White can play like in Shirov's game} 15. Rad1 $1 {And as
we have seen in similar variations, Black has not solved all his problems yet.}
f5 $5 (15... Rad8 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. g4 $5 {the misplaced h6-knight is a
recurring motive in these positions.}) 16. exf6 Qxe4 17. Nxe4 exf6 18. Rfe1 {
With correct play, Black should be fine, but White has some annoying threats
like Nd6 or Nc5, and with one or two errors the endgame can become very
difficult. His queenside pawn majority should also be easier to exploit than
black's kingside majority, which definitely offers him better practical
chances.} *

