1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. e5 $5 {This agressive
move can surprise Black as it is just the third most popular option.
Nevertheless, the positions arising from it are very interesting. White is
trying to take the initiative in the center quickly, seizing space and
attempting to disturb Black's development.} (6. Bd3 {is the classical and main
option,}) ({while} 6. Be2 {is also often seen}) 6... Nfd7 {This looks like the
only knight move worth playing for black. Other knight moves seem to be
inferior, as you can see in the analysis below.} (6... Ne8 {[%csl Ge8] The
knight is just badly placed here and hindering Black's development.} 7. Be3 (7.
Bc4 c6 8. Be3 Bg4 ({even} 8... Nc7 {doesn't really improve the knight}) 9. h3
Bxf3 10. Qxf3 d5 $2 11. Bd3 e6 12. O-O-O Qa5 13. h4 $40 {with a strong attack
coming in Huschenbeth,N (2548)-Maduro,S (1993) Paramaribo 2016}) 7... Bf5 $6 (
7... c6 $142 8. Bd3 b5 9. h4 $40 {Obolentseva,A (2364)-Egyed,J (2142)
Montevideo 2017}) 8. Bd3 e6 $6 9. Bxf5 exf5 10. Qe2 {White is going to have a
pleasant advantage due the natural plan 0-0-0 followed by h3-g4 with attack,
but after} d5 $2 {his life was even easier} 11. Qb5 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5] winning a
pawn Jovanovic,Z (2526) -Pejic,I (1871) Bosnjaci 2017}) (6... Ng4 $6 {is
rather provocative} 7. h3 Nh6 8. g4 $5 {[%csl Gh6] This leads to the already
familiar problems with Nh6 for Black.} f6 (8... f5 9. g5 Nf7 10. Bc4 e6 11. Qe2
{[%cal Gh3h5] White can always count on the h4-h5 plan. His position is much
easier to play.}) 9. Bc4+ Kh8 10. e6 $1 {[%csl Gh6] and Black had a difficult
position in Wang,H (2605)-Du,S (2399) China 2006}) (6... Nh5 $6 {is also a
strange place for the knight} 7. Be2 Bg4 {Can,E (2464)-Annaberdiev,M (2444)
Beijing 2008} 8. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ye4f2] a thematic maneuver as we will see. Here
it is already putting a lot of pressure on Black's position.} Bh6 {[%cal Yh5g7]
} 9. Nf2 $1 Bd7 (9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nxf4 11. g3 $18) 10. f5 $1 Bxc1 11. Qxc1
$16 {[%cal Yc1h6]}) 7. Bc4 {[%cal Ye5e6] After an aggressive move, White
continues with a normal, developing one. Yet, this move is not without venom
as the bishop is actively placed on this diagonal, creating the annoying
threat of e5-e6. Besides, in a positional sense White keeps a pleasant space
advantage and good control of the center. As I mentioned in the first chapter,
even in sharp variations it is important to limit opponent's counterplay as
much as possible.} ({The super aggressive} 7. h4 $5 {is the most principled
idea and may seem in the most accordance with White's intentions. However, I
don't like how the position becomes double-edged after} c5 $1 {shaking up
White's center} (7... h5 $2 {only helps White to accelerate the attack} 8. e6
$1 fxe6 9. Ng5 Nf6 10. Bd3 Qe8 11. Qe2 $40 {[%csl Re6,Rg6]}) 8. h5 cxd4 9. hxg6
(9. Qxd4 {seems to offer better chances}) 9... dxc3 {How to evaluate such a
position? It is just a mess...} 10. gxf7+ Rxf7 11. Bc4 e6 $1 12. Ng5 Nxe5 $3 (
12... cxb2 13. Bxb2 Qa5+ 14. Ke2 Nf8 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 {Sutovsky,E (2700)-Ivanchuk,
V (2768) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011} 16. Qxd6 $13) 13. Qh5 $1 $13 {with a very
complicated position. Maybe White's play can be improved earlier, but I don't
think that it is a good practical decision go for such lines when you have
easier continuations at your disposal. In situations like this, even when well
prepared, we can commit decisive mistakes when the tension grows and
everything depends on precise calculations and tactical details.}) 7... Nb6 {
The safest, winning a tempo and preventing e6.} (7... c5 $2 {I think this move
is very risky for Black now} 8. e6 $1 Nb6 (8... fxe6 {should be the lesser
evil, but then} 9. Ng5 {continues the attack.}) 9. exf7+ Kh8 {and here there's
a very important move to remember} 10. h4 $3 {Simply, a stunning move. At
first sight, the attack doesn't seem to be so strong. Even the engine is not
impressed at first. But if we look deeper...} Nxc4 (10... cxd4 $2 11. h5 $1 g5
12. Nxg5 h6 13. Qd3 $1 hxg5 14. h6 Bf6 15. fxg5 $18 {and the attack is
unstoppable.}) (10... d5 11. h5 $1 g5 12. Bb5 $1 cxd4 (12... a6 13. Be8 $18)
13. Nxg5 $1 {[%cal Gd1d3]} Bf5 14. Ne2 h6 15. Nxd4 $18) 11. h5 {At first the
computer is assessing this position as clearly better for Black, but when you
keep playing the moves, he suddenly changes the evaluation and realizes how
strong White's attack is in fact.} Bf5 (11... Rxf7 12. hxg6 Rf6 {Wirig,A (2496)
-Pel,B (2287) Montpellier 2015} 13. Rxh7+ Kg8 14. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gd1h5] is
winning for White} Nd7 (14... Rxg6 15. Nxg6 Kxh7 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Ne4 {[%cal
Ge4g5]}) 15. f5 Nf8 16. Qh5 Bxf5 17. Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 18. Bh6+ Kg8 19. Bxf8 {
[%cal Rh5h7]} Bxg6 20. Nxg6 Qe8 21. Qh8+ Kf7 22. O-O-O $1 $18) 12. hxg6 Bxg6 {
Black's position seems safe now, but then} 13. f5 $1 {and the attack continues}
Bxf5 (13... Bxf7 14. Ng5 Kg8 $8 (14... h6 15. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Rg5e6,Rc1h6]}) 15.
Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gh1h7,Rg5e6,Rc1h6] White has a lot of threats} e6 16. Rxh7 $1
exf5 {now a forced line follows:} 17. Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 18. Ne6+ Kf6 19. Bg5+ Kxe6
20. d5+ $1 Kd7 21. Qxf5+ Kc7 22. Bxd8+ Kxd8 $16 {Black has sufficient material
for the queen, but his king is exposed. White can continue simply with 0-0-0
and Ne4, which gives him a clear advantage.}) 14. Ng5 {around here the
computer finally starts to realize that Black's defense is very difficult, but
it is too late. White is actually winning, as the variations below prove:} Qd7
(14... Qc8 $142 15. Qh5 h6 16. Nd5 $1 {[%cal Yd5e7]} Nc6 17. Nf4 $1 {[%cal
Gf4g6]} N4e5 $8 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Rd2c3]}) 15. Qh5 h6 16. d5 $1
{[%cal Rc1h6,Gg5e6] Black is totally defenseless against White's pressure} Ne5
17. Ne6 $1 Rxf7 (17... Bg6 18. Qxh6+ $1 Bxh6 19. Rxh6+ Bh7 20. Nxf8 Qf5 21.
Rxh7+ Qxh7 22. Nxh7 $18) 18. Bxh6 Bxh6 19. Qxh6+ Bh7 {Again, it might seem
that Black has finally consolidated his position, but...} 20. Ne4 $1 {[%cal
Re4g5] one more attacker is coming!} Qa4 (20... Qe8 21. N4g5 Qg8 22. Nxf7+ Nxf7
23. Qxh7+ Qxh7 24. Rxh7+ Kxh7 25. Nc7 $18 {[%csl Ra8] Guseynov,A (2333)
-Shanava,K (2504) Istanbul 2017}) 21. N4g5 Kg8 22. Nxf7 Qe4+ 23. Kf1 $18 {
Laurent,B (2369)-Gulbas,C (2377) Belgium 2014 - In conclusion, this is a long
and critical variation, but it is not really a chaos like some other
variations. For the invested piece, White is pressing and attacking with
comprehensible moves, while Black's task is much harder.}) 8. Bb3 Nc6 {[%cal
Yc6a5] Black keeps developing pressure in the center and now has the Na5 idea
to get rid of the annoying Bb3. White has more space, but if Black manages to
trade some pieces and exchange pawns in center at a favourable moment, then
his position would be acceptable.} (8... c5 $6 {[%cal Yc5c4] is too hasty} 9.
dxc5 dxc5 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Be3 $1 Na6 12. Ng5 $1 {was already better for
White in Smith,A (2449)-Petersen,PB (2197) Helsingor 2015}) (8... Na6 {
prepares c5, but it is also a bit strange} 9. Be3 c5 10. Qe2 Bg4 11. O-O $14 {
In general, such positions are favourable for White as long as he has good
central control and his pieces are well developed, as it is in this instance.
Importantly, Black's Bg7 is restricted by the e5-pawn. In addition, in this
specific case also the Na6 is out of play. All of these positional edges gave
White better prospects in Grandelius,N (2647)-Hillarp Person,T (2546) Denmark
2015}) 9. a4 $1 {[%csl Yb3][%cal Ga4a5] I like this move a lot - White keeps
the bishop alive and at the same time threatens a5. I think that it is very
important to avoid exchanges in this position as White has a slight space
advantage.} (9. Be3 Na5 {and}) (9. O-O Na5 {give Black a decent position.})
9... a5 ({Black still tried a couple of times} 9... Na5 10. Ba2 c5 $6 {[%cal
Yc5c4] aiming to lock out the bishop on a2. However, having the Na5 out of
play looks like a high price to pay for this "achievement".} 11. dxc5 $1 dxc5
12. Qe2 c4 13. O-O Bg4 $2 {this exchange is a bad one for Black} 14. h3 Bxf3
15. Qxf3 Qc8 16. Be3 Rd8 17. Rad1 Qc6 18. Qxc6 bxc6 {now with the simple
sequence} 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Rd1 $1 {White kept a great advantage} Rxd1+ (20...
Rb8 $142) 21. Nxd1 {[%cal Ye3d2]} g5 (21... Nxa4 22. Bxa7 $18 {[%csl Ra4,Ra5]
[%cal Ya7b8,Yb8c7]}) 22. Bd2 Nb7 23. a5 Nd5 24. fxg5 Bxe5 25. Bxc4 {with an
extra pawn and a technically winning endgame in Karavade,E (2421)-Lorscheid,G 
(2238) Douglas 2016}) 10. h3 $1 {Another move that I like, again aiming to
make Black's life difficult by denying exchanges and relieving his lack of
space. There's no direct way to increase White's advantage, but it is always
easier to play with more space, slowly improving the pieces and the pawn
structure. Consequently, it is also easier for Black to make a mistake in a
cramped position.} Nb4 {Black tried this move in the two games played in this
position up to this point. This makes sense as the knight is placed better on
b4 and Black can try to push c6 or c5 at some point.} 11. O-O c6 (11... e6 12.
Ne4 d5 {was seen in the game Zufic,M (2395)-Saric,I (2553) but now} 13. Ng3 $14
{secures a stable advantage for White. After c3 the bishop can be improved to
c2 and active ideas like h4-h5 will be very strong in the future.}) (11... Bf5
$146 {doesn't really change much} 12. Be3 c6 (12... Qd7 $4 13. g4 Be6 14. d5
$18) 13. Nh4 $1 $36 {[%cal Yf4f5]}) 12. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gc2c3] A common maneuver
to reinforce the center.} N4d5 13. Qe1 $40 {[%cal Ge1h4] Thanks to his space
advantage and firm control of the center, White is ready to start active
operations on the kingside:} Kh8 14. Qh4 f6 15. Bd2 Be6 16. Rae1 $16 {White
has developed all of his pieces and kept a favourable position. Black had no
visible counterplay and had to stay passive in Gharamian,T (2657)-Henrichs,T 
(2492) Germany 2014-15} *

