1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. e5 dxe5 {In the previous
chapter, we have analyzed all knight moves at this junction. The pawn capture
on e5 is played the most, so it deserves a separate chapter. Black expects to
open some files and put pressure on White's center.} 7. fxe5 Nd5 (7... Nfd7 $6
{[%cal Yc7c5] Black plans to continue with c5 and destroy White's strong
center, but this retreat disrupts his development and White can immediately
take advantage of that with} 8. h4 $1 c5 $8 (8... h5 {stops the attack, but
after} 9. Bd3 {[%cal Re5e6]} Nb6 10. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yc2c3] white
prevents c5 break and prepares to reinforce the center with c3} Bg4 11. c3 N8d7
12. Nf2 $1 $16 {White is much better.}) 9. h5 cxd4 10. hxg6 $3 {another piece
sacrifice that makes life very difficult for Black.} dxc3 (10... hxg6 11. Qxd4
$18 {[%cal Rd4h4]}) 11. gxf7+ Rxf7 12. Bc4 {Black should play very precisely
now, not to get into a lost position quickly.} e6 $2 {Black didn't solve his
difficult task in the following game.} ({The right move is} 12... Qb6 $1 {
the point behind it being} 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 {[%cal Gf7e8,Ge8d8] when Black king
can run towards the queenside in order to find a safe place there.} 14. Qd5+ e6
(14... Ke8 15. Rxh7 cxb2 16. Bxb2 Qxb2 17. Rd1 $40 {White is at least
regaining the piece, for example} Kf8 $2 18. Qe4 {[%cal Ge4f5]}) 15. Ng5+ Ke7
16. Nxe6 $1 (16. Qc4 $5 {can be investigated}) 16... Qxe6 17. Bg5+ Nf6 (17...
Kf7 18. O-O+ $1 Nf6 19. Qd3 $1 Qxe5 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Qxh7+ Kf8 22. Rae1 Qd6
23. Re4 $18 {[%cal Ye4f4,Ye4g4]}) 18. Bxf6+ Bxf6 19. Rxh7+ Kf8 20. Qxe6 Bxe6
21. exf6 cxb2 22. Rb1 Nd7 23. Rxb2 Nxf6 (23... b6 24. Rb4 $1) 24. Rhxb7 $14 {
and White keeps good chances to play for a win, especially if he manages to
trade one pair of rooks.}) (12... cxb2 $2 {is too greedy} 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 14.
Ng5+ Kf8 15. Nxh7+ Kf7 16. Ng5+ Kf8 17. Rf1+ Bf6 18. Ne6+ $18) 13. Bxe6 Qe8 14.
Bxf7+ Qxf7 15. Ng5 $1 {[%cal Gd1d5,Gd1h5] keeping the deadly threats} cxb2 $2 (
15... Qc4 {was the only way to keep the game going} 16. b3 Qc5 17. Bf4 Nf8 18.
Qh5 $40) 16. Bxb2 Qc4 {[%csl Gb2] an important detail is that White does not
