Be3 $1 fxe5 (19... Nxe5 20. Nxe5 fxe5 21. Bxc5 Qc6 22. Ba3 {[%csl Gc4,Gd6]
with a better endgame for White}) 20. Bxc5 e4 21. Qxe4 Bxa1 22. Rxa1 $44 {
[%csl Gc4,Gd6] Of course this position needs some tests, but White's
compensation looks at least satisfactory. White can improve his pieces using
some maneuvers like Ba3, Qe3 and Nd2-e4 to support the passed pawns; or Re1 to
attack the e6-pawn. Black can obtain some counterplay via the f and b-files,
but at the same time he should be careful about mating threats along the long
diagonal. White has a plenty of plans to demonstrate his compensation, so I
think it is an interesting position to handle in a practical game.}) (8... Nxc3
9. bxc3 {looks just better for White, not only reinforcing the center, but
also opening useful avenues for his pieces like the b-file and the a3-f8
diagonal for the bishop.}) 9. Bb3 Nc6 {Compared to the similar positions
analyzed in the previous chapter, White should be more careful with his center
here, as Black is already putting pressure on d4 and e5. If White manages to
do some consolidating moves, like c3 and Be3, then he will be fine and enjoy a
pleasant advantage. Probably, Black should be fine with correct play, but the
fact that he doesn't have a clear plan to contest White's center makes his
position a little more difficult to play. For now, White's only problem is
that, as he was busy obtaining more space for his pieces, his development was
delayed and his king was forced to remain in the center for a while. Keep in
mind that white's positional priorities are to avoid exchanges that would
relieve Black's position and to protect the central pawns. Both are essential
to keeping the space advantage.} (9... Bg4 {This is a very interesting moment
to use a nice idea} 10. Ne4 $5 {[%cal Yc2c3,Ye4c5,Ye4g5,Ge4f2] As it was said
