{White enjoys a pleasant advantage, for example:} c6 21. Bg5 Nd5 22. Qd2 $14 {
[%cal Yc3c4]}) 17. hxg6 hxg6 (17... fxg6 $142) 18. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Yd1d2,Ge2g3,
Gf4h6,Yb3c2] White was much better and developed a strong attack against
Black's kingside in Hirneise,T (2431)-Nagy,E (2261) Budapest 2011. One very
easy plan is to follow up with Qd2-Ng3, threatening either Ne4 and Nxf5. In
some cases the bishop can be transferred to c2, threatening to trade for the
knight on f5 as well. The main problem for Black is that without his Nf5,
White would be able to trade bishops with Bh6, when his attack would become
very dangerous. This is why in this game Black went for g5, but this only gave
another target for White and left the Nf5 less protected, making his task even
easier.} *

