1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 {Now it is time to check other
continuations for Black besides 5...c5 and 5...0-0.} c6 {In order to avoid
more critical and forced positions, Black may play like this, keeping a dose
of flexibility. This move is seen in some other lines of the Pirc as well. It
can help Black to launch counterplay on the queenside with b5 or Qa5.} (5... a6
{is another pawn move that Black can try to keep his options open. White can
continue in the same active way} 6. e5 $5 Nfd7 ({In case of} 6... dxe5 $6 {
there is a strong novelty} 7. dxe5 $1 $146 {As we know from the chapter 1,
dxe5 is the best option when the Black king is still on e8} Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 $1 {
[%csl Gd5] the threat of Nd5 is a real danger for Black} Ng4 9. Nd5 $1 {
the presence of the move a6 makes Black's defense even more difficult as White
can play this immediately} Kd8 (9... Nf2+ $2 10. Ke1 Nxh1 11. Nxc7+ Kd8 12.
Nxa8 $18 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Ya8b6] and thanks to the weakness of the b6-square,
the Na8 has a route to escape, while his rival on h1 is not able to do the
same.}) 10. Ke1 {[%cal Yh2h3] Black is facing the same problems seen in
chapter 1 regarding h3 and side-lining the knight on h6.} h5 11. h3 Nh6 12. Bd2
$36 {[%cal Yd2a5,Ya1d1]}) 7. Bc4 {[%emt 0:00:03] White can just develop
normally along the lines analyzed in the chapters 2 and 3.} Nb6 8. Bb3 d5 $6 {
This was played in all of the games which featured this position, but we
already know how bad it is positionally for Black, as now the center is closed
and White can comfortably exploit his space advantage.} (8... O-O 9. a4 $1 a5
10. O-O Nc6 11. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Yc2c3] with typical ideas already seen in
chapter 3}) 9. a4 $1 e6 $2 (9... a5 10. O-O O-O 11. Qe2 Nc6 12. Nd1 $1 $16 {
[%cal Gc2c3,Gd1e3,Yb3c2,Yg2g4,Yf4f5] White's plan in this position is slow but
very strong: improve the bishop by c3-Bc2, then transfer the knight to e3, and
maybe after some preparatory developing moves, go for f5, possibly with g4
first. This plan is so simple and annoying that Black probably needs to create
some counterplay as soon as possible.}) 10. O-O (10. a5 $1 {would actually be
even stronger.}) 10... h5 11. Be3 Nc6 12. a5 $1 Nd7 13. Bf2 $16 {[%cal Yf2h4]
Christensen,T (2343)-Clausen,S (2188) Denmark 2017}) 6. Bd3 {White doesn't
need to rush with the e5-advance, although it remains the best way to proceed
in the long term, at the right moment.} O-O (6... Bg4 7. h3 {forcing the
exchange} Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {White remains with the bishop pair and a slight space
advantage:} Qb6 $5 {trying to prevent an easy development for White} (8... O-O
9. Be3 {[%cal Ye4e5,Ye1c1,Gg2g4,Gh3h4] promises White a strong attack in the
future}) 9. e5 $1 {White responds actively, trying to disturb Black's
development in turn.} Nfd7 {and now} (9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Nfd7 11. Rb1 $16 {
[%cal Yc1e3]}) 10. a3 $1 {[%cal Yc1e3] is a nice way to finish the development
with a clear advantage} Na6 (10... O-O 11. h4 $1 $40 h5 12. e6 $1) (10... d5
11. O-O e6 12. Be3 O-O 13. h4 $36) (10... Qxd4 $2 11. Be3 {[%csl Rd4] and the
