Nf6 (9... Nb6 10. h4 $40) 10. Ng5 $36 {and White has good prospects on the
kingside.}) 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {A different structure that those we have seen so far
has arisen. The key difference is that now Black has no c5, so White's center
is safe and this secures a small space advantage.} 9. O-O Nc6 (9... Bg4 {
Again this exchange doesn't help Black solve his problems.} 10. h3 Bxf3 11.
Qxf3 e6 12. c3 Nc6 13. Be3 f6 14. exf6 Qxf6 15. Rae1 Rae8 {White's advantage
is self-evident. A good way to proceed is to look for a way to open some files
on the kingside, when the bishop pair would become very useful.} 16. Qg4 a6 17.
h4 $1 Ne7 18. h5 $1 {Now Black rushes to protect his position} Nf5 19. Bd2 gxh5
20. Qxh5 Qh4 {but after} 21. Qxh4 Nxh4 22. g3 Nf5 23. Kg2 {[%cal Yf1h1,Yg3g4]
Black's situation is just positionally desperate and White had no problems to
increase the pressure and win in So,W (2640) -Guseinov,G (2625)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2009}) 10. c3 {Black has tried many moves here, but in any
case White is able to keep an advantage.} a5 $6 {A totally harmless plan.} (
10... a6 11. Qe1 {[%cal Ye1h4]} e6 12. b3 {[%cal Yc1a3]} Re8 13. Qg3 b5 14. a3
Rb8 15. Ng5 f5 16. exf6 Qxf6 {Now, White can develops his pieces like in the
game So-Guseinov, centralizing and then going to the kingside} 17. Bd2 Ne7 18.
Rae1 Nf5 19. Qh3 h6 20. g4 $1 Ne7 21. Kh1 $1 $40 {Doncevic,D (2355)-Bastian,H 
(2330) Germany 1992}) (10... f5 $2 {this is played with the aim to block the
kingside, but the only thing that Black manages with this move is to bury both
of his bishops.} 11. Qe2 a6 12. Be3 dxe5 13. dxe5 $1 {[%cal Ge3b6]} Kh8 14.
Rad1 Be6 15. Qf2 $16) (10... dxe5 {may be the best try} 11. Nxe5 $5 (11. fxe5
f6) 11... Nxe5 12. fxe5 Qb6 {[%cal Yg7e5] Quinones Mena,J (2056)-Caurapan
Osses,J (2208) Santiago 2007 now White can go for a slightly better endgame,
with a better structure and more space.} 13. Qb3 $1 Qxb3 14. axb3 $14 {[%cal
Yc1g5,Ya1a5]}) 11. Kh1 a4 {was seen in Caspi,I (2450)-Manolache,M (2545) Tel
Aviv 2011. White can just ignore Black's idea and keep developing with} 12. Be3
a3 13. b3 {when perhaps the critical possibility for black is} dxe5 14. dxe5 $1
(14. fxe5 f6 15. exf6 exf6 $11 {[%cal Yc8e6,Yd8d7]}) 14... f6 $5 {but after} (
14... Bg4 15. Qd2 Rc8 16. Rae1 $14) 15. exf6 Bxf6 (15... exf6 $2 16. f5 $1 $16)
16. Qd2 Qd6 (16... d4 $2 17. Bc4+ {[%csl Rd4]}) 17. Rae1 {White's position
remains easier to play.} Be6 18. Ng5 $1 $14 {White is well-centralized and the
weaknesses in Black's camp will start to tell soon.} *

