1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 Bg4 {Besides pawn moves like 5...
a6 or 5...c6, Black has some rare developing moves and this one is the
relatively most popular. However, personally I don't think that it is a very
reliable option.} (5... Nc6 $6 {such moves are typical for modern openings -
Black tries to provoke White's advances in center in order to attack these
pawns later.} 6. Be3 {at the first moment, White doesn't rush forward and just
continues developing.} (6. d5 {doesn't appeal to me} Nb8 {[%csl Yg7][%cal
Gc7c6,Ge7e6] White has gained a tempo and space in centre, but in return the
Bg7 is stronger now, and Black has possibilities like c7-c6 or e7-e6 to
destabilize White's centre}) 6... O-O 7. e5 $1 {We are already used to seeing
this move in many lines, and once again it is the correct advance. Now two of
Black's pieces are feeling uncomfortable: the restricted Bg7 and the dislodged
Nf6.} Ng4 (7... dxe5 8. dxe5 $1 {This recapture is an exception - in general
after Black had already castled, White should recapture with the f-pawn. But
here the inclusion of the move 6.Be3 is an important detail that works in
favor of dxe5.} Ng4 (8... Qxd1+ $2 9. Rxd1 {leaves White much ahead in
development} Ng4 10. Bc1 {[%cal Yh2h3,Yg2g4]}) 9. Bg1 {[%cal Yh2h3] Black is
about to have practical problems with an already known motif in such positions:
the Nh6 out of play. In some games black tried to exploit his lead in
development with an early break:} f6 10. Bc4+ Kh8 11. h3 Nh6 12. Qe2 {If White
succeeds playing 0-0-0 or Bf2 followed by 0-0 and completes his development,
then his position would be much better and easier to play.} fxe5 13. fxe5 e6 ({
for example} 13... Nf7 14. Rd1 Qe8 15. Bh2 $1 $14 {[%cal Ye1g1]}) 14. Bf2 {
White is ready to finish development and keep the advantage, so Black tried}
Rxf3 $6 15. Qxf3 Nxe5 {but after} 16. Qe2 Nf5 17. Rd1 {he did not have enough
compensation in Shirov,A (2580)-Johansson,J (2460) Stockholm 1990}) (7... Nd7
$6 8. h4 $1 {I like White's prospects with respect to launching quick attack
in kingside} Nb6 9. h5 Bg4 10. hxg6 fxg6 {a sad necessity, as opening the
h-file would be fatal} 11. Be2 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 $16 {White has the
bishop pair and a better pawn structure, which gives him good chances in
almost all endgames. Also, opportunities for kingside attack should not be
discarded. White turned these positional advantages in a material one very
easily in Drenchev,P (2465) -Roa Alonso,S (2382) Madrid 2015}) 8. Bg1 Nh6 $5 {
trying to anticipate h3, but it does not change much} (8... dxe5 9. dxe5 {
just transposes to 7...dxe5}) 9. h3 f6 $2 (9... dxe5 $142 10. dxe5 Be6 11. Bd3
Nf5 12. g4 $5 Nfd4 13. Be4 $1 $36) 10. d5 Nb8 11. e6 $16 {and Black's position
is nearly strategically lost Renet,O (2515)-D'Amore,C (2410) Haifa 1989}) (5...
Na6 {This looks like a safer option as the knight is useful on a6 in many
positions and Bxa6 is not a serious threat.} 6. e5 $1 {this was played only in
a few games, but it is potentially very unpleasant for Black, as the games in
the database show} (6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O {would transpose to the main positions
of this variation, but is not in accordance with our idea of taking the
initiative with White as soon as possible.}) 6... Nd7 (6... dxe5 7. fxe5 $1 {
and here, despite Black king still standing on e8, White should take with the
f-pawn, as the ideas related to Nb5/d5 after dxe5 are harmless.} Nd5 {This
position was reached in Oleksienko,M (2618) -Mikhalsky,V (2188) Lutsk 2016 but
in that game White went for an equal endgame. Instead he had a stronger option}
8. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Yc2c4] a move that we have also seen in similar positions,
especially in chapter-3. White keeps c7-c5 under control and prepares to kick
the knight with c2-c4, building a strong centre.} Bf5 9. Bxa6 $1 bxa6 10. Nc5
$16) 7. h4 $1 {since Black does not have a dangerous way to strike back in the
center, this move is very strong. We can see that when Black postpones
castling, his lack of development allows White to start active operations in
the center and on the kingside.} h5 {Pelyushenko,I (1926)-Rotunno, G (2046)
Amantea 2010} (7... Nb6 8. h5 O-O 9. h6 $1 Bh8 10. Bxa6 bxa6 11. Qe2 Bg4 12.
O-O $14 {[%csl Yh8]}) 8. e6 $1 {this break is always strong when Black plays
h5 as the g6-pawn is insufficiently protected.} fxe6 9. Bd3 Nf8 10. O-O {
Besides the threats of a direct attack, Black faces some issues with
development, too.} Nb4 (10... c5 11. Bxa6 $1 bxa6 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8
14. Be3 Rb8 15. Na4 $16) 11. Be2 Nd5 12. Ne4 Nf6 13. Neg5 $16 {[%csl Re6,Re8,
Rg6][%cal Ye2d3,Gf1e1,Gc2c4,Gd1c2] White is already much better. He can
develop strong pressure against the g6 and e6-pawns, and his pieces are going
to find good squares very easily.}) 6. h3 {Naturally, White grabs the bishop
pair.} Bxf3 7. Qxf3 {[%csl Gc1,Gf1] Besides the pleasant space advantage and
the bishop pair advantage, White has prospects of opening the position either
in the center or on the kingside. From my point of view, Black's achievements
are that the trade of Bc8 gives him some extra space to arrange the pieces and
connect the rooks, as well as some flexibility of the pawn structure. This
being said, I don't think that these points are enough to reach the equality.}
c6 {Fighting against e4-e5.} (7... Nc6 {is another plan, trying to fight back
in the center as soon as possible.} 8. Be3 e5 9. Bb5 $1 {This shows how
dubious Black's idea is, as the bishops can play an active role, while open
files are favourable for White.} exd4 (9... O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. dxe5 dxe5 12.
f5 $16 {the pawn structure and the difference between the minor pieces,
especially bishops, are clearly in White's favour}) (9... exf4 10. Qxf4 O-O 11.
O-O-O $16 {is another type of position that is much better for White. The
centre is not fixed, meaning that the bishops can support future advances and
breakthroughs.}) 10. Bxd4 O-O 11. Bxc6 $1 {giving back the bishop to obtain a
static advantage in the form of a superior pawn structure.} bxc6 12. O-O-O $1 {
[%cal Ye4e5] Black should already deal with the dangerous threat of e4-e5} Nd7
13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. e5 $1 d5 15. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] with a strong attack for
White in Gonzalez de la Torre,S (2285)-Izeta Txabarri,F (2469) Subijana de
Alava 2002}) 8. Be3 Qa5 {Black is, very understandably, afraid to place his
king on g8 already.} (8... O-O 9. O-O-O $1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh3h4,Ye4e5] due to
the nature of this position, Black should try to create some complications,
but White's attack looks stronger and more threatening} Qa5 10. Kb1 $1 {
always a good prophylatical move} Nbd7 (10... b5 $2 11. e5 $1 {[%cal Yf3a8]})
11. g4 e6 {Kotronias,V (2597)-Roktim,B (2405) Mumbai 2003 White can calmly play
} 12. Be2 {[%cal Yg4g5] and his attack is just impossible to hold off:} b5 (
12... Rab8 13. g5 Nh5 14. Qf2 {[%cal Re2h5]}) 13. e5 $1 Nd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15.
h4 {[%cal Yh4h5] with h5-Qh3 coming, it is difficult to give a good advice for
Black. He should look for some counterplay with} dxe5 16. dxe5 f6 17. h5 $1
fxe5 18. hxg6 exf4 19. Qh3 $1 hxg6 (19... h6 20. g5 $1) 20. Qh7+ Kf7 21. Rh6 {
[%csl Gg6]} Ne5 22. Bxf4 Rh8 {[%csl Rh7]} 23. Bxe5 $1 Rxh7 24. Rxh7 {[%csl Gg7]
} Rg8 25. Rf1+ $18 {White is going to have too much material for the queen,
and Black king remains in danger.}) 9. O-O-O d5 $5 (9... O-O 10. Kb1 {would
transpose to 8...0-0}) (9... Nbd7 10. Kb1 $1 {now Black is unable to play the
same idea from the main line. Instead, he can continue} O-O-O {avoiding a
direct attack, but after} 11. g4 $16 {White's position is still clearly
preferable}) 10. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ya2] This is Black's idea in order to avoid
a cramped position and keep the material balance. Unfortunately for him, this
approach doesn't fully solve his problems either.} (10... Nfd7 11. f5 $18 {
is not only bad for Black, but actually losing at once.}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qg4
$5 {[%csl Gc8] The point behind this move is that White gains a tempo by
creating a mating threat.} (12. Qxe4 {is simple and good, too. White is
trading a central pawn for a rook's one, and this way keeping a strong centre
and a mobile structure that can be exploited at any moment.} Qxa2 13. c3 Qa1+
14. Qb1 Qxb1+ 15. Kxb1 e6 16. g4 $16 {and White won easily just seizing the
space on the kingside in Egger Mancilla,J (2410)-Letelier Martner,R (2215)
Santiago de Chile 1993}) 12... e6 (12... O-O 13. Bc4 e6 14. Qe2 Nd7 15. Bd2 $16
{[%cal Re2e4] Perez de Aranda,L (2216)-Sotnikov,T (2005) Madrid 2010}) 13. Bc4
{[%csl Re4][%cal Yc4e6] White protects his pawn and is ready to attack e4, at
the same time keeping attacking ideas like Bxe6 handy.} h5 $6 {Helping White's
task, but black's situation doesn't inspire much hope either way.} (13... O-O
14. h4 $18 {[%cal Yh4h5]}) 14. Qe2 b5 15. Bb3 h4 16. Bf2 $18 {[%cal Ge2e4]
Despite Black's collaborative play, this is still a nice example of how easily
White can exploit the advantage of the bishop pair; Parker,J (2510)-Gross,S 
(2330) Berliner 1998} *

[Event "?"]
