[White "Chapter 6"]
[Black "1...g6 and 4...a6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B06"]
[Annotator "IM Renato Quintiliano"]
[PlyCount "47"]
[EventDate "2017.??.??"]
[Source "ChessPublishing"]
[SourceDate "2014.11.09"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 {This is another common move order, which is
often employed by the Modern Defense's players. The point behind leaving the
knight on g8 is that Black can save this tempo and expand on the queenside
with a6-b5 or c5 instead. Secondly, he is taking advantage of the open
diagonal for Bg7. And finally, the e4-e5 advance loses some of its strenght as
it does not hit the knight on f6. However, despite all of these small plusses,
black is still seriously neglecting his development and leaving his king in
the center.} 4. f4 {We are going to follow the same idea even without the
knight being placed on f6. White seizes space on the kingside and is ready to
take the iniative at the first possible moment by advancing the central pawns.}
a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7,Yb8d7,Yc7c5] I think this is an ambitious line for Black
since some strong grandmasters have played it, such as Fabiano Caruana. Black
trusts that his king is safer in the centre than on the kingside and hopes to
be the first launching a flank attack, with fast development of his queenside
pieces.} 5. Nf3 (5. a4 {prevents b7-b5, of course, but after} Nc6 {[%csl Yb4]
having the b4-square at disposal proved to be useful for Black} 6. Be3 (6. d5
Nb4 7. Be3 (7. Nce2 $5 {[%cal Yc2c3]} a5 $1 8. c3 Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]}) 7... e6
$15 {one recurring problem which White can face in Modern positions is
unstable center if his central pawns lose support of the pieces.}) 6... Nf6 {
[%cal Yf6g4]} 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 (8. h3 Nh5 $5 {[%csl Yg3]} 9. Ne2 {now Black
can take the initiative in centre with} e5 $1 10. fxe5 dxe5 11. d5 Nd4 $1 {
and White is in trouble already} 12. Nexd4 exd4 13. Bxd4 Re8 $36 {[%cal Re8e1]
and Black had a strong initiative in Kokaia,G (2101)-Bortnyk,O (2588) Georgia
2016}) 8... Nb4 $5 9. O-O Ng4 10. Bd2 c5 $1 {then Black gets a nice
counterplay against White's centre} 11. d5 {Pribyl,J (2263)-Mihok,O (2509)
Banska Stiavnica 2016. Here Black could have continued with} f5 $1 {[%csl Yd5,
Ye4] and White would have problems holding these pawns together.}) 5... b5 ({
If Black tries to keep some flexibility and not reveal his intentions yet with
} 5... Nd7 $6 {then White can exploit this by means of} 6. Bc4 $1 {and Black
is already in an unpleasant situation} e6 (6... b5 $4 {now allows the trick} 7.
Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 8. Ng5+ $18 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5e6]}) (6... Nh6 7. a4 $1 {
[%csl Yd7,Yh6] Now this move is strong as the knight is already committed to
d7, so there is no Nc6.}) 7. f5 $1 {this aggresive move is reminiscent of a
sort of Closed Sicilian positions, where White plays f5 just to provoke the
opening of Black's position and to get some attacking lanes for his pieces.}
Nb6 (7... exf5 8. exf5 Nb6 $2 {is a worse move order} 9. fxg6 $1 Nxc4 $2 10.
gxf7+ Kxf7 11. Ng5+ {with Qh5, 0-0 and a deadly attack coming}) 8. Bb3 exf5 9.
O-O $1 {[%cal Yb3g8,Yf1f8] White has a dangerous initiative in return for the
pawn} Ne7 (9... h6 {prevents Ng5, but doesn't help Black with his development}
10. a4 $1 a5 {Marek,M (2418)-Ponizil, C (2493) Prague 2016} 11. exf5 Bxf5 12.
g4 $1 {a difficult move to spot, but a very strong one} Be6 (12... Bxg4 13.
Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 14. Ng5+ Ke8 15. Qxg4 hxg5 16. Bxg5 {[%cal Ya1e1] and again
Black is defenceless against White's attack} Bxd4+ 17. Kh1 $1 $18) 13. Bxe6
fxe6 14. Qd3 Ne7 15. Nh4 $40) 10. Bg5 {White just continues his development
and increases the pressure.} O-O (10... Be6 11. exf5 $1 Bxf5 {Boeven,M (2017)
-Gerhardt,P (1958) Cuxhaven 2006} 12. Re1 f6 13. Bf4 {[%csl Yb3][%cal Yb3g8]}
d5 14. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5]}) 11. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1h4] This queen transfer
to the kingside is also seen in the Closed Sicilian positions previously
mentioned.} h6 $2 (11... Kh8 $8 {preparing to contest Qh4 with f6} 12. e5 $1
dxe5 13. dxe5 Qe8 14. Qh4 Nc6 15. Bf6 $40 {Black has survived the first wave
of attack, but his position remains very unpleasant.}) (11... Be6 12. exf5 $18
{[%cal Ye1e7]}) 12. Qh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge7,Gh6] The bishop is untouchable, and
White's attack was too much for Black in Harika,D (2539)-Tan, Z (2502) Teheran
2017}) 6. Bd3 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black plays this move first in order to attack
White's centre with c7-c5 as soon as possible.} (6... Bb7 {Against this move
order, I recommend} 7. Qe2 $5 {which scores well for White} (7. O-O {is the
main line}) (7. e5 Nd7 {transposes to the text}) 7... Nd7 (7... c5 $2 {is
actually very bad now due to} 8. dxc5 $1 dxc5 9. e5 $1 {[%csl Gg8][%cal Yd3e4]
Black will be left with the usual problem of his passive kingside pieces} Nh6
10. Be4 {I like how White obtained a clearly superior position by simple and
natural moves in the following game:} Qc8 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. Qe4 $5 {exchanging
queens would leave White with an easier development} Nc6 13. Be3 $16 {Black
was under serious pressure already in Yu,Y (2729)-Maghsoodloo,P (2584) Doha
2016}) ({Another game of the chinese GM went like this:} 7... e6 8. e5 (8. f5
$1 $146 {is a good improvement for White}) 8... Ne7 9. a4 $1 {this is why
White can allow the advance b7-b5 - he can undermine it later.} b4 10. Ne4 O-O
11. O-O Nd7 12. c3 $14 {and White has a pleasant advantage due to his firm
control of the centre Yu,Y (2721) -Iordacheschu,V (2583) Baku 2015} (12. exd6
$6 cxd6 13. Nxd6 $2 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Bxd4+ {[%cal Yd7c5] and Black is fine})) (
7... b4 {hits the knight but doesn't really change the character of the
position much.} 8. Nd1 Nd7 9. O-O c5 10. d5 Ngf6 {Deszczynski,A (2341)
-Petrosian,T (2648) Warsaw 2013 here White could play} 11. c4 {[%cal Ye4e5]}
bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Rb1 Rb8 14. c4 $16 {[%cal Ye4e5] with very good
prospects.}) 8. e5 $1 {transposes to the notes of 7...Bb7}) 7. e5 $1 {[%csl
Ye4] Creating tension in the center and vacating the e4-square, which could
become useful both for the knight and bishop.} (7. Qe2 $6 {would be well met
now by} c5 $1 {and Black is the first one to strike in the center.} 8. e5 (8.
dxc5 Nxc5 {[%cal Yc5d3] is harmless for Black}) 8... cxd4 9. Be4 dxc3 $1 {
This is not a particularly difficult exchange sacrifice.} 10. Bxa8 Qc7 $1 {
aiming to pick up another pawn, with nice compensation. After} 11. exd6 $2 Qb8
$1 $19 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc3b2] Black was completely winning in Low, Z (2245)
-Seul,G (2405) Basel 2017}) 7... c5 {This immediate counterblow has been
Black's main move.} (7... Bb7 8. Qe2 {[%cal Ge5e6] This is not the main move
here, but an interesting one. It is threatening e5-e6 and thus forcing Black
to commit with his pawn structure.} e6 (8... c5 $2 {it is important to be
aware of situations when c5 is not good for Black in this variation, like here:
} 9. Ng5 $1 {- better than the immediate e5-e6, as now the knight joins to the
attack as well. There's no safe way for Black after this:} cxd4 (9... Nh6 10.
e6 Nf8 $2 11. Bxb5+ $1 axb5 12. Qxb5+ Nd7 13. Qxb7 $18 {Hovhannisyan,R (2589)
-Minasian,A (2525) Yerevan 2012}) (9... Qb6 10. e6 fxe6 11. Qxe6 O-O-O 12. Nd5
$1 $16 {Sigurjonsson,G-Sznapik,A Tbilisi 1974}) (9... e6 10. Nce4 $1 Bxe4 11.
Nxe4 $16) 10. e6 $1 {this is much stronger now than on the previous move.} f5 (
10... f6 11. exd7+ Qxd7 12. Ne6 dxc3 {Shi,D (2132)-Cherniaev,A (2451) Windsor
2016} 13. f5 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge6] the Ne6 is just a monster, and the threats of
Nxg7 and fxg6 are too much to handle for Black}) 11. exd7+ Qxd7 {Surprisingly,
White has lost all the 3 games played in this position. The position is
unbalanced and it seems like Black has a dangerous initiative with his central
pawns advancing and attacking White's pieces. But in fact White can manage to
keep an advantage by returning the piece for those pawns!} 12. Nb1 $1 $146 {
White had tried Ne6 and Nd1 until now} e5 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. a4 $1 {White
should react actively} h6 (14... b4 15. Bc4 Bd5 16. Bxa6 $1 Bxg2 $1 17. Rg1 Bc6
18. Bc4 Bd5 19. Nd2 $16) 15. Nf3 e4 16. axb5 Ne7 17. bxa6 $1 Bc6 {the only way
to regain the piece} (17... O-O 18. Bc4+ Kh7 19. Nfd2 $16 {and White is nearly
winning}) 18. Bc4 $1 exf3 19. gxf3 {White returned the piece, but kept a small
material advantage. Truth be told, the position is still a little complicated}
Bd5 20. Bxd5 Qxd5 21. O-O {White is still ahead in development, for example}
Kf7 22. Rd1 Rhc8 (22... Rhe8 23. Nc3 $1 Qc5 24. Qb5 $1) 23. Na3 $1 {[%cal
Ya3b5,Yc2c3] In the previous game the knight was slightly out of play on d1
and then re-routed to f2, but it did not play an active role there. From b1,
on the other hand, White can maneuver it to a3 and b5, from where it can put
pressure on the d4-pawn, with good prospects.}) (8... Nh6 {looks safer, but it
is not sufficient as White can play the usual positional game against the Nh6}
9. a4 $5 {again this move appears to be a good option, provoking unfavourable
advances for Black.} (9. Ne4 {is the main move, also with good results}) 9...
b4 (9... O-O $6 {is a sacrifice that fails to give enough compensation for
Black} 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 {Stamenkovic,D (2418) -Souza Neves,A (2239)
Florianopolis 2017} 12. Nxb5 {[%csl Yc7] winning a precious tempo} Bxf3 13.
Qxf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3 c6 15. Na7 $1 c5 16. Nc6 $16) 10. Ne4 O-O (10... d5 $2 {
simply kills any hope of counterplay in the centre for Black} 11. Neg5 $1 e6
12. Bd2 a5 13. g4 $1 {a very creative and strong idea} Nxg4 14. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7
15. Ng5+ Ke7 16. Qxg4 $40 {[%csl Re7] Black managed for to survive for a
