1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 {This is another common plan. Black prepares the
attack on White's centre with d7-d5 when he would block his pawns on dark
squares. After that, he typically plays on the light squares and/or looks to
undermine White's structure with c6-c5 or f7-f6 at the right moment.} 4. f4 {
Again, this space-grabbing move is a good option for white.} d5 (4... Qb6 $5 {
is a tricky move, as White can't play Be3, and after} 5. Nf3 d5 $1 {Black
aggresively attacks white's center. However, white might take a materialistic
approach and play} (5... Nh6 {is more flexible. I think that White can play
simply} 6. Bd3 $146 {which is apparently a novelty, but after} d5 7. e5 Bg4 {
we reach a position that has already been seen in practice. However, now} 8. h3
$1 $146 {is truly a novelty. After} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 O-O (9... Qxd4 $2 {grants
White too many tempi:} 10. Be3 Qb4 11. O-O-O $44 d4 $2 12. a3 $1 Qb6 13. Bf2
$16) (9... Nf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Qd3 Na6 12. Be3 $16 {White keeps the space
advantage and both Black's minor pieces are misplaced.}) 10. Bd2 Qxd4 11. O-O-O
{White has a strong attack coming in the next moves, for example} Nd7 12. g4 e6
13. Kb1 {it's very difficult suggest something for Black here, for example} f6
$2 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Qe2 $1 (15. g5 $2 {was not possible due to} Bxg5) 15...
Nf7 16. g5 Bg7 17. h4 e5 18. h5 $1 {and Black is lost} e4 19. hxg6 exd3 (19...
hxg6 20. Be3 exd3 21. Qh2 $1 $18) 20. gxf7+ Rxf7 21. cxd3 $18 {Black has no
counterplay, and White's attack continues}) 6. exd5 $5 (6. e5 Bg4 {Black wants
to develop a quick pressure against d4 pawn by capturing the f3 knight and
going Nh6-f5, taking advantage of the queen being placed on b6 early.} {
Here too, instead of holding on to the d4 pawn, the engine recommends a pawn
sacrifice:} 7. Bd3 $5 $146 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qxd4 {when White obtains an unpleasant
initiative with} 9. Be3 Qb4 10. a3 $1 {and after the queen goes back, White
can play 0-0-0 followed by the pawn advances on the kingside. Taking the
poisoned pawn} Qxb2 $4 11. Kd2 $1 {would end up badly for black, with his
queen getting trapped.}) 6... Bg4 $1 {In such modern lines Black tries to take
the initiative against White's centre as soon as possible, even at the cost of
a pawn} 7. h3 {I think this is the simplest way for White to reach a good
position} Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bxd4 (8... Nf6 $5) 9. Bd2 $1 {an important move,
preparing both Na4 and 0-0-0} Nf6 (9... Bg7 10. O-O-O Nf6 {Bhuiyan,A (2049)
-Delorme,A (2084) Sautron 2001} 11. Be3 Qc7 12. Kb1 O-O 13. g4 $40) 10. Na4 Qd8
11. c3 {there's no way back for this bishop} Bb6 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. Nxb6 axb6
14. a3 O-O 15. Bb5 $14 {Of course in such open positions, the bishop pair
gives White excellent chances; Ionescu,D (2343)-Doncea,V (2424) Calimanesti
2014}) 5. e5 h5 {Black tries to make White's expansion on the kingside as
difficult as possible.} (5... Qb6 $5 {This is a typical idea to make it more
difficult for White to develop the Bc1. Also, in some variations the pin with
Bg4 is unpleasant as d4 can be hanging. Thus, I would recommend} 6. Na4 {
and after} Qc7 {both sides have achieved their goals: Black can claim that the
knight is slightly misplaced on a4, while White now has the reinforcing move
c2-c3 at his disposal. It's important remember the correct move now} 7. Nc5 $1
{The knight should not remain on a4 for too long.} (7. c3 $6 b6 $1 {and the
Na4 could remain misplaced.}) 7... Nh6 8. Be2 {by developing the bishop first,
White avoids ideas with Bg4} b6 9. Nd3 c5 10. c3 O-O 11. Nf3 Bg4 12. Nf2 $1 {
White safely protected the centre and found an useful role for the knight. His
position is, therefore, preferable.} Be6 (12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 e6 14. g4 $1 $16
{Black is cramped and with the usual Nh6-problem}) 13. O-O Nc6 $6 {although
this is a natural and developing move, White found a nice way to get a clear
advantage} 14. dxc5 $1 bxc5 15. Ng5 $1 {because of the weakness of d5-pawn,
Black has to accept a strategically inferior position} Qb6 (15... Qd7 16. Nd3
$1) 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Nh3 $16 {With the Bg7 permanently out of play, White is
practically strategically winning and he indeed converted without difficulties
in Balogh,C (2644)-Markowski,T (2567) Legnica 2013}) 6. Nf3 Nh6 (6... Bg4 7. h3
$1 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 {Black's plan is to curb White's ambitions on the kingside
by playing h5-h4. But two nice games from GM Ivanisevic have shown how White
should proceed in this case} 9. Be3 (9. g4 $2 Qh4+ $1) 9... h4 10. Bd3 Nd7 (
10... Ne7 11. O-O Nf5 12. Bf2 Nd7 13. Ne2 Rc8 14. Rfd1 Bf8 {Naturally, after
placing the knight in f5, Black improves the bishop.} 15. b3 {This is the plan
for White: to seize more space on the queenside while Black has to spend
