a3. White pieces safely protect all squares along the c-file. Ivanisevic
skillfully managed to outplay his opponent in Ivanisevic,I (2656)-Warakomski,T
(2492) Warsaw 2016}) 11. O-O Nh6 12. Ne2 Nf5 13. Bf2 Qe7 14. b3 {again the
same plan is the best way for White to play for an advantage} f6 15. c4 O-O-O {
This time, Black hopes to find a safe place for the king on the queenside and
to complete his development at same time.} 16. Rac1 Kb8 17. c5 Rdf8 {Black is
about to look for the initiative on the kingside by opening some files, but
after} 18. Bxf5 $1 exf5 19. b4 Rc8 20. b5 $1 $40 {White had a strong attack
and won in Ivanisevic, I (2643) -Indjic,A (2538) Qatar 2014}) 7. Bd3 Bf5 {
As we have seen previously, Black usually fails to solve his problems by
trading this bishop for the Nf3, so another option is to exchange it for his
counterpart on d3. Regardless, White can still play the same plan.} (7... Bg4 {
transposes to positions similar to those analyzed in the previous notes} 8. h3
Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 10. Be3 h4) 8. O-O e6 9. b3 $1 {This b3-c4 plan should be
remembered in such structures when advances on the kingside are not possible.
Black still has a solid position, similar to some Advanced Caro-Kann
variations, but just like in those lines, he suffers a bit from lack of space.}
(9. Be2 $5 {was played in another interesting game where White used the same
idea.} Bg4 (9... Nd7 10. h3 $1 {could give some trouble for Black with the Bf5}
) 10. Be3 Nd7 11. Bf2 Nf5 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 h4 14. Ne2 Nb6 15. b3 $1 Nc8 $2
{this maneuver doesn't help Black} 16. c4 Nce7 17. Qe1 $1 {nice improvement of
