[White "Chapter 8"]
[Black "1...g6 and 3...c6 without h5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Annotator "IM Renato Quintiliano"]
[PlyCount "27"]
[EventDate "2018.??.??"]
[Source "ChessPublishing"]
[SourceDate "2014.11.09"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 d5 5. e5 Nh6 {This leaves a bit more
freedom for White on the kingside. Black has different options and move orders,
but in general his plan is the same: attack White's centre by means of c6-c5
and f7-f6, with or without Bg4xf3. White should be careful with the pawns, as
if the centre remains safe, he can enjoy a pleasant space advantage and
Black's pieces would stay without active possibilities, notably the Bg7. If
Black trades the bishop with Bg4-xf3, then in some cases opening the position
in centre can be good for White due the bishop pair. I think that in this
variation White should be less worried about specific variations, it's more
important to know Black's plans and nice examples from grandmaster's practice
of how to deal with them.} 6. Nf3 Bg4 (6... O-O 7. Bd3 {sometimes White can
reinforce the centre by means of Ne2 and c2-c3} f6 8. O-O Bg4 9. h3 (9. Ne2 {
[%cal Yc2c3] looks like an interesting option}) 9... Bxf3 10. Rxf3 {I simply
prefer White here. The bishop pair and the space advantage promise him an
easier game.} fxe5 (10... e6 11. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Yc2c3] an instructive maneuver
that should be remembered. It is very important for White to keep the centre
under control.} fxe5 12. dxe5 $1 {White rightly changes the pawn structure,
keeping the kingside closed as after fxe5 Rxf3 Black has chances for
counterplay on that side of the board.} Nd7 (12... c5 13. c3 Nc6 14. Be3 Qe7
15. a3 $1 {[%cal Yb2b4]} g5 $2 (15... c4 $142 16. Bc2 Nf5 17. Qd2) 16. b4 c4 $2
{Black exchanges the queen for three pieces, but it is not a good deal here}
17. Bc5 cxd3 18. Bxe7 dxe2 19. Qxe2 Nxe7 20. fxg5 Nf7 21. Qb5 $36 {and the
queen was stronger in Jones,R (2398) -Chatalbashev,B (2552) Cardiff 2017}) 13.
c3 Qe7 14. Bc2 {White plays very carefully. Naybe because of that Black
thought that it was time to start concrete operations with} g5 $2 (14... Nf5
15. Nd4 $14) 15. Rg3 $1 {[%cal Yg3g8] suddenly Black is under serious pressure}
gxf4 16. Nxf4 Kh8 17. Rxg7 $1 Qxg7 18. Nh5 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Yc1h6] and White
won in Eljanov,P (2739) -Arnaudov,P (2435) Ohrid 2017}) (10... Qb6 $2 {[%csl
Yd4][%cal Yf6e5] Black's threats are well answered by} 11. Be3 $1 Qxb2 $2 12.
Na4 Qa3 13. Nc5 $18 {[%cal Gc5e6] Garcia Amoros,P (2162)-Jimenez Villena,F 
(2231) Benidorm 2002}) 11. fxe5 $1 {since the recapture Qxf3 is available,
White can recapture with the f-pawn} e6 (11... Nd7 12. Rxf8+ Nxf8 13. Ne2 $1 {
this typical maneuver is always useful to improve both the pawn structure and
the knight.} Qb6 {Khismatullin,D (2583)-Novikov,S (2532) Ramenskoe 2006 - now
White could have played} 14. c4 $1 {which gives him a strong initiative, for
example} Ne6 15. c5 $1 Qc7 16. Qc2 {threatening Bxg6! hxg6 Bxh6 Bxh6 Qxg6+
winning} Nf7 17. Be3 b6 18. Rf1 $1 {[%cal Gd3g6] Again Bxg6 is dangerous} Rf8
19. b4 $16 {White's advantage is evident, his pieces have more freedom and he
will be pressing for a long time.}) (11... Rxf3 12. Qxf3 e6 13. Ne2 $1 Nd7 14.
c4 $1 {and again White obtained a pleasant position with this move} Qe7 15.
cxd5 exd5 16. Qg3 {[%csl Ye5]} c5 $2 17. Bg5 Qe8 18. Re1 cxd4 {Malaniuk,V 
(2515)-Kantsler,B (2430) Tallin 1998} 19. Nf4 $1 $18 {[%cal Ge5e6]}) 12. Rxf8+
$1 {White should play like this in order to fulfill his plan Ne2-c3.} Qxf8 13.
Ne2 $1 Qe7 (13... c5 14. c3 Nc6 15. Be3 Nf5 16. Bxf5 $1 {even after the
exchange, White keeps a slightly better position} Qxf5 17. Ng3 Qf7 {
Areshchenko,A (2687) -Makarov,M (2520) Olginka 2011} 18. Qg4 {[%cal Ya1f1]
would have offered him nice prospects.} Rf8 19. Rf1 Qd7 20. Rxf8+ Kxf8 21. Ne2
$1 {[%cal Ge2f4,Yh3h4,Yh4h5] and White is still pressing in the endgame}) {
If Black doesn't play c6-c5, then it's time for White break in the centre with}
14. c4 $1 {after} Nd7 15. cxd5 cxd5 (15... exd5 $142 16. Qb3 Nf8 17. Be3 $14 {
[%csl Ye5][%cal Ya1f1]}) 16. Bd2 Nf7 {White was clearly better in Andreescu,N 
(2140)-Brandis,I (2120) Bucharest 1997 and after} 17. Rc1 Nb6 18. a4 $1 {
Black was facing unpleasant defence.}) (6... f6 {transposes to 6...0-0} 7. Bd3
Bg4 (7... O-O 8. O-O Bg4) 8. O-O O-O) 7. h3 $1 {I think that White can pose
some unexpected problems for Black by accelerating his attack on kingside,
taking advantage of the fact that he did not play h5.} Bxf3 8. Qxf3 f6 (8...
Nf5 9. Ne2 h5 {Now Black tries to slow down White's advance on the kingside,
but it is too late} 10. g4 $1 Nh4 11. Qf2 {[%csl Yh4] the Nh4 is out of play}
e6 12. Bd2 Bf8 {[%cal Yf8e7]} 13. Ng3 Be7 14. O-O-O Na6 15. gxh5 gxh5 16. Be2
$16 {[%csl Rh5] Santo Ruiz,M (2154)-Aranaz Portugues,J (2147) Seville 2013}) (
8... Qb6 $6 {is nicely refuted:} 9. g4 $1 Qxd4 10. Be3 Qb4 11. O-O-O {and
White has full compensation for the pawn, for example} e6 12. h4 $1 Nd7 13. Kb1
O-O-O 14. a3 Qa5 15. h5 $44) (8... O-O $2 {is bad, after} 9. g4 $1 {[%cal
Yf4f5]} e6 10. h4 $1 $40 {[%cal Yh4h5] White is already launching a dangerous
attack}) 9. Bd3 O-O 10. exf6 $5 {with this move White simply aims to obtain a
better pawn structure} (10. h4 $5 {[%cal Yh4h5] also looks very promising and
deserves attention}) 10... Bxf6 (10... Rxf6 {Onischuk,V (2601) -Ehlvest,J 
(2536) Jurmala 2017} 11. Be3 Nd7 12. O-O-O {[%cal Yg2g4,Yh3h4] White is ready
to begin attacking operations like g2-g4 and h3-h4-h5. If Black tries
something active like} e5 $2 {it can be contested by} 13. Nxd5 $3 cxd5 14.
Qxd5+ Kh8 15. dxe5 Rf8 16. Bb5 $1 Nb6 17. Qxb7 {White is grabbing a lot of
pawns for the piece. After} Qc8 18. Qxc8 Raxc8 19. g4 $1 {[%csl Gh6] his pawns
prove to be very strong.}) (10... exf6 11. f5 $1 {[%csl Yg7] Black has some
trouble after this} Nxf5 12. Bxf5 gxf5 13. O-O Qb6 14. Ne2 Nd7 {White was not
materialistic and continued creatively. He could have also played simply c3
and regain the pawn on f5 with better prospects.} 15. Be3 Qxb2 16. Ng3 $1 {
[%cal Yg3f5,Yf3g4] looking for attacking possibilities} Rf7 17. Nxf5 Qa3 18.
Qh5 Nf8 19. Bh6 $1 $18 {Oleksienko,M (2616)-Azaladze,S (2468) Al Ain 2015}) 11.
Be3 ({better than} 11. Ne2 e5 $1) 11... e5 {trying to get rid of the backward
pawn makes sense, but after} (11... Qb6 {Paragua,M (2508)-Vedmediuc,S (2468)
Istanbul 2012} 12. Ne2 $1 $146 Qxb2 13. O-O Qa3 14. Rab1 b6 15. g4 Nd7 16. Qg3
$36 {[%cal Yf4f5,Yg4g5]}) 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. O-O-O $1 {White finishes
development and starts to look for an attack on the kingside} Bg7 (13... Bxc3
$2 {destroys White's king protection, but also gets rid of the important
defending piece.} 14. bxc3 Qa5 15. Bd4 Qc7 16. c4 $1 Nd7 17. cxd5 c5 18. d6 $1
$18 {[%cal Gd3c4] Krause,M (2151)-Benninger,R (2139) Hanau 2008}) 14. h4 $40 {
[%cal Yh4h5] And although Black can put up some resistance, White's attack is
clearly very dangerous.} *

